  <h5>Why Scientists Believe This Regular Meal Kills Cancers</h5>
  <hr />
  <h6>
    By Alice Bekerly | 3 min read <br />Thursday | 5<sup>th</sup> Feb, 2024
  </h6>
  <p>
    Cancer is one of the most challenging diseases facing humanity, but
    scientific studies are uncovering powerful, natural tools in the fight
    against it. Recently, researchers have focused on the anti-cancer properties
    of specific foods, such as broccoli, turmeric, and green tea.
    <br />
    One particularly promising discovery highlights a combination of cruciferous
    vegetables like kale and broccoli, rich in sulforaphane—a compound shown to
    slow the growth of cancer cells. Adding foods high in antioxidants, such as
    berries and walnuts, further strengthens the meal’s protective effects.
    <br />
    Studies have also suggested that regularly eating a Mediterranean diet,
    which is high in healthy fats from olive oil, whole grains, and fish, could
    significantly reduce cancer risk by lowering inflammation and oxidative
    stress.
    <br />
    While no single meal guarantees immunity from cancer, consistently
    incorporating such foods into your diet may help prevent or even fight
    cancer development. Scientists are hopeful that dietary changes can be a key
    addition to modern cancer therapies.
  </p>
